The paper presents a parallel computational framework for Non-negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) that uses MPI for interprocessor communication. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the scalability of the algorithm and benchmarks it on massive dense and sparse data matrices, which could also fit under the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of NMF in different domains such as text mining, video analysis, and social networks, indicating that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of different NMF and Non-negative Least Squares (NLS) algorithms, which could fit under the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents a flexible and high-performance framework for NMF, which could also fit under the Systems and Control (cs.SI) sub-category.
